The eloquence of his style is secured by smooth, flow- ing periods which show striking skill in the effectiveness of their word order. There is no monotony of lengthy sentence, for Livy's vivid imagination soon quickens every situation into lively action which the reader seems actually to see. Not the least important means for this effect is seen in the finished speeches interspersed in the work. These and the personal incidents so graphically told give to the work noW, as they did in ancient timeS, one of its greatest charms, the element* of human interest. ‘

Livy's diction represents the tendency of his age to vary from the more strict norms of Ciceronian prose. .
